body:
Hi @samnewhook 

Hm, interesting, this might be an issue with tensorflow versions. Could you try to do the following:
1. build the model the way it's done in `train_miccai2018` (i.e. using `networks.miccai2018_net`)
2. use `model.load_weights`

Does this work?
Thank you @adalca, much appreciated, this method works! I am using python=3.6 and tensorflow=1.12.0 with CUDA 9.0 FYI.
glad it helped, and thanks for the info. I'll add it to things we need to look into... :)

I ran into a similar problem when using `register.py`, after some investigation, I found that the MICCAI version is trained with:

    flow_vol_shape = model.outputs[-1].shape[1:-1]
    loss_class = losses.Miccai2018(image_sigma, prior_lambda, flow_vol_shape=flow_vol_shape)

and the custom_layer defintion contains:

    custom_objects = { [......]
                 'recon_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10).recon_loss, # values shouldn't matter
                 'kl_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10).kl_loss        # values shouldn't matter
                 }
The values don't matter, but the type of the values matters, it seems with the most recent version on Github. The following code fixed the error "*TypeError: Expected int32, got None of type '_Message' instead.*".

    custom_objects = { [......]
                 'recon_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10, flow_vol_shape=[32]).recon_loss, # values shouldn't matter
                 'kl_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10, flow_vol_shape=[32]).kl_loss        # values shouldn't matter
                 }

issue.title: Fix load Error on newer Tensorflow versions
issue.body: `Register.py` does not accept `flow_vol_shape` to be `None` but expects an iterable.

body:
One more think about two lines. If we use cvpr model and the model trained in custom dataset, then we have error in two about lines because cvpr used ncc and mse loss. I fixed it by changed it to losses.NCC().loss

Update: I meant

```
        custom_objects = {'SpatialTransformer': nrn_layers.SpatialTransformer,
                 'VecInt': nrn_layers.VecInt,
                 'Sample': networks.Sample,
                 'Rescale': networks.RescaleDouble,
                 'Resize': networks.ResizeDouble,
                 'Negate': networks.Negate,
		 'loss': losses.NCC().loss,
		 'loss': losses.Grad('l2').loss
                 #'recon_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10).recon_loss, # values shouldn't matter
                 #'kl_loss': losses.Miccai2018(0.02, 10).kl_loss        # values shouldn't matter
                 }
```
Does having the recon_loss in there for the CVPR model give you an error during registration only (no training) ?
If we use pretrained model from cvpr, then the code works. But I I retrain the model, I cannot use the above comment lines. They said the loss is not found.

Hm, very interesting. Did you change something about the training. 
Did you use `save_model` or `save_weights` to save?

I just use original code without modify anything in train.py

[train.txt](https://github.com/voxelmorph/voxelmorph/files/3556618/train.txt)
